1. Data Normalization and Transformation

Normalization - DeSeq2 Normalization & Transformation

dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = adjusted_counts,
                              colData = combined_metadata,
                              design = ~ 1)
converting counts to integer mode
Warning: NAs introduced by coercion to integer rangeError in validObject(.Object) : 
  invalid class DESeqDataSet object: NA values are not allowed in the count matrix
dds1 <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = adjusted_counts1,
                              colData = combined_metadata,
                              design = ~ 1)

ddsDE1 <- DESeq(dds1)

deseq_norm_counts1 <- counts(ddsDE1, normalized = TRUE)

#Blind = true - estimates normalization factor independently for each sample
vsd1 <- vst(ddsDE1, blind = TRUE)

#Extract normalized values from VST transformed object vsd
vsdassay1 <- assay(vsd1)
#Looking at the most variable genes

#calculate variance 
gene_vars <- rowVars(vsdassay)

#sort in decreasing order
top1000 <- order(gene_vars, decreasing = TRUE)[1:1000]
top5000 <- order(gene_vars, decreasing = TRUE)[1:5000]
top10000 <- order(gene_vars, decreasing = TRUE)[1:5000]


#subset to only includ genes from the previous step
vsdassay_top1000 <- vsdassay[top1000, ]
vsdassay_top5000 <- vsdassay[top5000, ]
vsdassay_top10000 <- vsdassay[top10000, ]

#samples = stacked bars. Basically shows how likely a sample is to belong to one cluster at different k values. 1 solid color = sample belongs only to that color, and can be considered as 'representative' of that cluster. Multiple colors - sample shares consensus to multiple clusters.

3. Clustering

# Calculate the distance matrix using Euclidean distance
dist_matrix <- dist(t(vsdassay_top5000), method = "euclidean")

# Perform hierarchical clustering using the complete linkage method
hc <- hclust(dist_matrix, method = "complete")

# Plot the dendrogram
plot(hc, cex = 0.4)

c1 <- cor(vsdassay_top5000, method="spearman") #calculate correlation
d1 <- as.dist(1-c1)  #because correlation is a similarity measure and we want a distance
hc1 <- hclust(d1, method="complete")
plot(hc1, cex = 0.4, labels = combined_metadata$Cell_Line)


combined_metadata$Cluster <- cc5$consensusClass

#Create a dds object
dds1 <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = adjusted_counts,
                              colData = combined_metadata,
                              design = ~0 + Cluster)

#~0 + Cluster" --> no intercept in the model. Useful for categorical variables, (Cluster) that we want to model without comparing it to a specific reference level
ddsDE1 <- DESeq(dds1)
deseq_norm_counts <- counts(ddsDE1, normalized = TRUE)
vsd <- vst(dds1, blind = TRUE)

#Extract normalized values from VST transformed object vsd
vsdassay <- assay(vsd)
plotPCA(vsd, intgroup = c("Cluster")) + geom_text_repel(aes(label=combined_metadata$Name))

#Cluster Comparisons - compares each cluster to the average of the other 4 clusters

cluster3_results <- results(ddsDE1, contrast = c(-(1/3), -(1/3), 1, -(1/3)))
